{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568546","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568546"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:17:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:17:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21000"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"21000","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/21000"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.38,0.46,0.01,0.1,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13875"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100511"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13875","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13875"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21000"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82928"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"45"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"274"},{"type":"tags","id":"1131"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"},{"type":"tags","id":"11641"},{"type":"tags","id":"13336"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33482"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34343"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43742"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100511","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/100511"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of right knee pain that is worsening with activity. She reports difficulty walking more than 100 metres and climbing stairs. She does not report any upper limb joint pain. She has a medical history of hypertension and hypercholesterolaemia. Her regular medications include amlodipine and atorvastatin. She works part-time as a librarian and lives alone in a single-level home.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her body mass index is 32 kg/m\u00b2. Her right knee has mild effusion, crepitus on movement, and tenderness over the medial joint line. Range of motion is limited by pain. X-rays show moderate medial compartment osteoarthritis of the right knee.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate instruction regarding cane use for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Use the cane in the right hand","Use the cane in the left hand","Use the cane on stairs only","Use the cane in either hand depending on comfort","Use a frame instead of a cane"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptomatic knee osteoarthritis affecting her right knee. Non-pharmacological management options include weight loss, exercise, and walking aids such as canes (NHMRC Level 2 evidence). When prescribing a cane for unilateral knee osteoarthritis, proper technique is essential to maximise benefit.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUse the cane in the left hand\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct approach for this patient with right knee osteoarthritis. Using a cane on the contralateral (opposite) side to the affected knee reduces load on the medial compartment of the knee joint by up to 50%. This biomechanical principle works because the cane creates a wider base of support and shifts the center of mass away from the affected side, reducing the adduction moment at the knee joint.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUse the cane in the right hand\u003C/strong\u003E would be incorrect as this would not effectively reduce the load on the right knee. Using a cane on the ipsilateral (same) side as the affected knee does not provide the biomechanical advantage needed to reduce medial compartment loading.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUse the cane in either hand depending on comfort\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect advice. While comfort is important for adherence, the biomechanical principles of cane use are paramount for effectiveness. The contralateral side placement is based on evidence, not patient preference.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUse the cane on stairs only\u003C/strong\u003E would limit the benefit of the walking aid. Patients with knee osteoarthritis typically experience pain with all weight-bearing activities, not just stair climbing. The cane should be used consistently during walking to provide ongoing load reduction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUse a frame instead of a cane\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for patients with bilateral knee osteoarthritis according to Osteoarthritis Research International (OARSI) guidelines, but this patient has unilateral disease affecting only the right knee. A frame would provide more stability but is unnecessarily cumbersome for unilateral disease and may reduce adherence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to proper hand placement, the cane should be adjusted to the correct height (creating 20-30\u00b0 elbow flexion when the tip is placed 10 cm lateral to the ankle), and the patient should be instructed to place weight through the cane at the start of the stance phase when the affected leg contacts the ground. Patients should be advised that using a cane may initially feel awkward and slow their walking pace, but with 1-2 months of regular use, they typically adapt and find it beneficial.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Canes for knee osteoarthritis should be used on the contralateral side to the affected knee to reduce medial compartment load.","Proper walking cane height is determined by achieving 20-30\u00b0 elbow flexion when the cane tip is placed 10 cm lateral to the ankle.","Patients should be instructed to place weight through the walking cane at the start of the stance phase for maximum benefit."],"references":["RACGP Handbook of Non-Drug Interventions: Walking cane for knee osteoarthritis. Accessed at: https://www.racgp.org.au/clinical-resources/clinical-guidelines/handi/a-z/w/walking-cane-for-knee-osteoarthritis"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82928"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21000"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/82928"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-26T06:55:00+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-26T06:55:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13875"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100511"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"45","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/45"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83e\uddbd","name":"Rehabilitation Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position"